{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/machine-reads-bertrand-russell-ff4eb63bc25c", "time": 1683003109.970005, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/machine-reads-bertrand-russell-ff4eb63bc25c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Machine Reads Bertrand Russell. Natural Language Processing (NLP)\u2026 | by Almis Povilaitis | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Machine Reads Bertrand Russell", "description": "One of my secret goals is to read more of Bertrand Russell\u2019s works; Russell was a polymath and prolific writer across a range of subjects, including philosophy, logic, social issues, and mathematics\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.gutenberg.org/", "anchor_text": "Gutenberg", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://pypi.org/project/Gutenberg/", "anchor_text": "Python\u2019s Gutenberg package", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/welcome.ipynb", "anchor_text": "Colab", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://www.nltk.org/", "anchor_text": "NLTK", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/amueller/word_cloud", "anchor_text": "Wordcloud", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/reimagining-plutarch-with-nlp-part-1-24e82fc6556", "anchor_text": "previous article on Plutarch,", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://gist.github.com/mlai-demo/4ed02f2bba7e9faf1691f05eab8510d2", "anchor_text": "text cleaning and word count,", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemmatisation", "anchor_text": "lemmatize", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://gist.github.com/mlai-demo/4ebd22e29211162d39679edc0ef05a83", "anchor_text": "lemmatized text into word cloud", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://gist.github.com/mlai-demo/366434adc539dade03bbfcf9d98263ac", "anchor_text": "text titles without the path and file extensions", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-negative_matrix_factorization", "anchor_text": "Non-Negative Matrix Factorization", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_semantic_analysis", "anchor_text": "Latent Semantic Analysis", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_Dirichlet_allocation", "anchor_text": "Latent Dirichlet Allocation", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://escholarship.org/uc/item/34g5207t", "anchor_text": "Sparse Principal Component Analysis", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://github.com/mlai-demo/NLP_Russell", "anchor_text": "Github code", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "http://mathworld.wolfram.com/FrobeniusNorm.html", "anchor_text": "Frobenius Norm", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@samsachedina/demystified-kullback-leibler-divergence-3971f956ef34", "anchor_text": "Kullback-Leibler Divergence", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Itakura%E2%80%93Saito_distance", "anchor_text": "Itakura-Saito Distance", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://iq.opengenus.org/tf-idf/", "anchor_text": "TF-IDF (Term Frequency\u2013Inverse Document Frequency)", "paragraph_index": 21}, {"url": "https://github.com/mlai-demo/NLP_Russell", "anchor_text": "available on Github", "paragraph_index": 24}], "all_paragraphs": ["One of my secret goals is to read more of Bertrand Russell\u2019s works; Russell was a polymath and prolific writer across a range of subjects, including philosophy, logic, social issues, and mathematics. Naturally, I thought that asking my computer to do some of the reading on my behalf would help, especially while we still can tell computers what to do. So let\u2019s grab some texts from Gutenberg and teach the machine to generate some insights.", "First things first, we need to import the texts to be analyzed. For that, I would recommend using Python\u2019s Gutenberg package instead of the generic file import packages because it allows easy removal of Gutenberg\u2019s rather lengthy disclosures in each document. If we\u2019re dealing with just one text, that would not be such a big deal, since the removal can be done manually, but in this case, we\u2019ll be bringing over ten texts. To set up Gutenberg on Google\u2019s Colab:", "The entire code is adjusted to run on Colab, so if you are running it on your machine instead, ignore the snippets for packages that you may already have locally. As you may already know, Colab setups are temporary and each time we need to upload everything that is not provided to all users by default. If using a Jupyter Notebook on your computer, you may want to adjust the window width as per below (change the percentages to fit your own preferences):", "In this tutorial, we\u2019ll be using NLTK, Wordcloud, and Scikit-learn libraries, and all of them have their own lists of stop words (very common and other words that would not add much value to our analysis). For consistency, let\u2019s just use the scikit-learn version throughout the tutorial, but include some extra words which I did not expect to be very useful:", "Let\u2019s import the texts assuming the Gutenberg package has already been installed:", "Leveraging the code from the previous article on Plutarch, let\u2019s do text cleaning and word count, where we\u2019ll remove some stop words, short words, numbers, syntax, tokenize the text, and count most frequent words:", "Let\u2019s check how many words there are and how many of them are unique:", "We get 216,893 words, of which 15,377 are unique. Using this pre-processed text, to make the insights more meaningful let\u2019s lemmatize it (i.e. remove inflectional endings and return base form of words) and draw a word cloud:", "We\u2019ll see that while the entire text has the same 216,893 words, the unique words dropped to 13,656.", "Let\u2019s put the lemmatized text into word cloud:", "The word \u201cthing\u201d becomes very prominent presumably due to combining \u201cthing\u201d and \u201cthings\u201d, so we might as well check how frequently it is used:", "Here is the output indicating that \u201cthing\u201d is now the most frequent; it was impossible to tell looking just at the word cloud:", "Russell\u2019s top words are general and abstract: thing, point, relation, space, world, fact etc. Overall, the top vocabulary represents a mixture of scientific, philosophical, and political words, indicating the diversity inherent in the text.", "Before we move on, let\u2019s copy and rename the ten individual texts from Gutenberg\u2019s indices to something that would resemble actual names, and then extract and sort just the text titles without the path and file extensions:", "There are quite a few topic modeling techniques, such as Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (NMF), Latent Semantic Analysis (truncated Singular Value Decomposition), Latent Dirichlet Allocation, and Sparse Principal Component Analysis \u2014 in the interest of space, in this tutorial we\u2019ll touch upon the first, and cover the other three in the Github code.", "All of the methods are very different, so checking and manipulating their component parts is very important as one tries to achieve better results. For example, scikit-learn shows the following for NMF:", "E.g. for beta-loss (measuring distance between NMF and target matrix), we have three choices: in addition to the default Frobenius Norm, we can also try out Kullback-Leibler Divergence and Itakura-Saito Distance. Solver itself can also be changed, from the default coordinate descent to multiplicative update solver (required for Itakura-Saito).", "We\u2019ll skip lemmatization this time for the wrong reason of keeping this tutorial shorter \u2014 but the technique is the same as shown above. Let\u2019s vectorize the text and create a numpy array as some of the above mentioned methods cannot process sparse matrices (NMF is OK with either, but sparse takes longer to process):", "And here is what we get:", "Let\u2019s check how various text address top four topics:", "There is (luckily) no overlap between the text on Bolshevism and on Geometry; Geometry\u2019s topics have good matches with the texts on Analysis of Mind, on Knowledge, as well as on Mysticism and Logic. Meanwhile, the document dealing with Bolshevism shared top topics with the text on Political Ideals, on Why Men Fight, and on Roads to Freedom.", "Last but not least, let\u2019s run TF-IDF (Term Frequency\u2013Inverse Document Frequency) to measure pairwise similarity among the ten texts:", "After converting the matrix which contains the similarity scores into the Pandas dataframe, we can easily visually examine the results:", "Yes, Geometry is still very different from Bolshevism!", "In this short tutorial, we leveraged popular NLP techniques to extract information from texts, including word cloud, topic modeling, and text similarity. We leveraged NLTK, Wordcloud, and Scikit-Learn along the way. Code covered in this tutorial (and more) is available on Github.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data-Driven Insights & Strategy. \u2764\ufe0f Lifelong learning and Statistics / ML / AI / Data Science. All views are my own."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fff4eb63bc25c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fmachine-reads-bertrand-russell-ff4eb63bc25c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fmachine-reads-bertrand-russell-ff4eb63bc25c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_col